<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Probate will be needed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MY HUSBAND and I have made identical wills leaving everything to each other
and thence to our married daughter. The house is on a tenancy-in-common
basis (50/50) to enable the surviving spouse to alter, if required, the
terms of the will within two years of a testator's death by a deed of a
family arrangement. Does the will have to go to probate should one of us
die? Has the 'deed of variation' been abolished?
We confirm that the will would have to go to probate. The deed of variation
has not been abolished.
This reply was provided by Barry Stillerman of Stoy Hayward.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
