<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / International Company News: Dow Jones income up at Dollars
30.9m for quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LOWER interest expenses and improved advertising revenue at the Wall Street
Journal helped Dow Jones, the newspaper's owner, post net income of Dollars
30.9m in the first quarter, up from Dollars 16.1m a year ago.
The comparable 1992 earnings, however, were affected by a restated one-off
net charge of Dollars 10.8m, taken because of changes in accounting for
taxes and employee post-retirement benefits. Excluding the special charge,
Dow Jones' first-quarter earnings this year were up 15 per cent on 1992.
Consolidated operating income for the first quarter rose 4.6 per cent to
Dollars 65.3m, on revenues of Dollars 463.4m.
Operating income from the company's business publications jumped 37.6 per
cent to Dollars 31.8m.
At the flagship Wall Street Journal, advertising lineage rose 5 per cent in
the January-to-March period.
Increased spending on technical product development, however, meant
operating income from the information services division, which includes the
Dow Jones/ Telerate electronic news service, fell 12.9 per cent to Dollars
34.5m.
Earnings were also lower at Ottaway Newspapers, Dow Jones' regional
community newspaper division, where income fell almost 6 per cent during the
quarter to Dollars 3.7m. The company said that income at a number of Ottaway
titles was hit by the big storm that struck large sections of the eastern US
in mid-March.
