<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / Anglo-Scots pipeline is mooted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Enterprise, the development body in Scotland, may study the
feasibility of building a privately funded pipeline to carry water from
southern Scotland and northern England to the drought-prone south of
England.
The pipeline, which would involve a 140-mile tunnel through the Pennines,
might cost Pounds 1.5bn. The idea has run into opposition, as the Scottish
Office considers privatising the water industry .
Scottish Enterprise may contribute Pounds 500,000 to a two-year project
study. Consulting engineer Mott MacDonald is understood to be interested, as
is Bank of America.
The scheme would take water from the rivers Nith, Dee and Annan in Scotland,
gather water from the rivers Eden and Esk in north-west England before going
to Kielder reservoir in Northumbria. The pipeline would then go by tunnel to
Carsington, where it would link with the water supply system for East Anglia
and south-east England.
