<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / Fowler link to prison escorts 'not improper'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE party officials were last night at pains to distance Sir Norman
Fowler, the party's chairman, from embarrassment surrounding Britain's first
private prisoner escort service, after it emerged that he is a director of a
company that shares the same ultimate parent.
Officials said that the board on which Sir Norman sits has no responsibility
for any of the work carried out by Group 4 Escort Services, which has
experienced three escapes since starting work last week on a five-year
contract covering the east midlands, South and North Yorkshire, Lincolnshire
and Humberside.
For the past three years Sir Norman has been a non-executive director of
Group 4 Securitas, a subsidiary of Dutch-based Group 4 Securitas
International.
Group 4 Securitas is the parent company of all Group 4 companies operating
in Britain, with the exception of those - such as Group 4 Escort Services -
which offer remand and court services.
Mr Alun Michael, a Labour home affairs spokesman, said that the directorship
illustrated the 'unhealthy' relationship between the Conservative party and
that part of the private sector which has a specific interest in the process
of privatisation.
Group 4 said last night there was 'absolutely nothing improper' in Sir
Norman's involvement with the group.
The latest escape came when a 20-year-old man facing traffic charges in
Derby broke out of the van taking him to court.
Mr David Evans, general secretary of the Prison Officers Association, said
yesterday he was not surprised at what had happened and he predicted further
escapes: 'This recurring nightmare will go on as long as this government
continues with its dogmatic policy of contracting out prison escorting.'
The prison service acknowledged 'significant difficulties' had been
experienced in the first few days.
Group 4 claimed that two of the escapes were due to failures in the special
vehicles used to transport prisoners. It insisted that its staff were
properly trained to carry out the tasks.
