<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / Failed bank monitored for several months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England closely monitored Roxburghe Bank for several months
before it went into administration on Wednesday, it has emerged.
Administrators are examining the operation of the business, including its
unusually high volume of deposits from overseas and the uncertainty about
the level of provisions required against bad loans.
The directors of Roxburghe, which was based in Mayfair in London, decided on
Tuesday to apply to the High Court for an administration order under UK
insolvency law.
Mr Keith Vaz, the Labour MP for Leicester East, said yesterday he would be
seeking an urgent meeting with Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, when MPs
return next week from the Easter recess.
Mr Vaz said that five banks directly serving Britain's Asian community had
now either been closed by the Bank or had voluntarily shut down and it would
take 'a great deal of explaining' to demonstrate that 'all of this is just a
coincidence'.
Mr Vaz referred to last month's disclosure by the Bank that in 1991 it had
launched financial lifeboats for a number of small- and medium-sized banks.
The Bank needed to explain why it had adopted different criteria when
dealing with institutions such as Roxburghe Bank, he said.
Mr Tony Lomas, one of the joint administrators from accountants Price
Waterhouse, said Roxburghe needed to seek protection from its creditors
because it would have been unable to meet demands for the increasing amount
of withdrawals before the end of April.
He said there were also concerns about whether it had net liabilities,
because it had Pounds 45m in assets at the end of February against Pounds
40m in liabilities plus the need to make further provisions of up to Pounds
6m.
The effective closure of the bank is the fourth in the past year to affect
the Asian community directly since the collapse of the Bank of Credit and
Commerce International in 1991.
Equatorial Bank and Mount Banking have since both ceased taking new
business. Albaraka International Bank's deposit-taking activities have been
suspended.
Mr Lomas said Roxburghe's Pounds 40m in liabilities was about evenly split
between cash deposits and loans to small Asian businesses in the south of
England. The largest loan was for about Pounds 2m.
He said most of the depositors were from overseas, predominantly based in
India and Kenya, with some accounts holding hundreds of thousands of pounds
each. Only about 10 per cent of the depositors lived in the UK.
The bank already had about Pounds 1m in provisions against bad debts, and
there was currently a debate about the size of additional provisions which
needed to be made of between Pounds 1m and Pounds 6m.
Under administration Roxburghe can theoretically continue to accept new
deposits from existing customers although none can currently make
withdrawals. The Bank has forbidden the bank from accepting deposits from
any new customers.
Mr Lomas said he would be writing in the next day or two to all depositors
and expected to provide them with a full report well within the three months
allowed for a report to creditors under administration procedures.
The accounts for the year to December 31 1991 show loans to three of the
directors of Pounds 120,000 and to two directors in 1990 of Pounds 87,000.
They also show an account with a credit of Pounds 43,000 in the name of J H
Shah, one of the directors, and another with a credit of Pounds 7,000 to J &amp;
R Shah Associates, a company controlled by Mr J H Shah and Mr R H Shah,
another director.
</TEXT>
