<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / Peres would meet Jerusalem Arabs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR SHIMON Peres, the Israeli foreign minister, said yesterday that he would
not object to talking to Palestinians from east Jerusalem, agencies report
from Jerusalem.
The Clinton administration in the US has proposed that Israel accept Mr
Faisal Husseini, a prominent east Jerusalem Arab, as head of the Palestinian
negotiating team in order to coax Palestinians back to negotiations, set to
resume in Washington on April 20.
Mr Peres stressed on Israeli army radio that excluding Arab negotiators from
Jerusalem was a policy of the previous, right-wing Likud government in
Israel, which had argued that to talk with such people would mean conceding
Israel's claim to rule the city.
Mr Peres added that he has 'never ruled out Faisal Husseini.' He said: 'On
the ground, Faisal Husseini heads the Palestinian team. The Americans are
speaking with him. We are not deaf or blind.'
Mr Husseini, who has close ties to the Palestine Liberation Organisation,
has been denied a formal role in the talks because Israel has objected to
sitting down with Arabs from Jerusalem.
