<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / US Budget: Subsidies to be cut - Agriculture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE 1994 US agriculture budget reduces programmes by 5.8 per cent below last
year's level but still leaves Dollars 63bn (Pounds 41.7bn) with which to
manage the nation's food supply, writes Nancy Dunne in Washington.
Farm subsidies, Dollars 17bn in this year's budget, are supposed to shrink
to Dollars 12bn in 1994 if the weather, the Russians and the competition
co-operate. The Agriculture Department plans to limit payments to farmers
who earn less than Dollars 100,000 in off-farm income; this is expected to
save Dollars 75m this year and Dollars 470m in 1994-97.
The administration also proposes to save Dollars 12m this year by cutting
honey subsidies and Dollars 10m by limiting wool and mohair incentives.
Another Dollars 52.3m will be deleted from the 1994 market promotion
programme, which provides assistance in overseas promotions.
After 1995 the administration expects even larger savings by expanding from
15 to 25 per cent the acreage which will be ineligible for subsidies.
Other savings are expected through agency consolidations, charging user fees
and reforming the crop insurance programme.
</TEXT>
