<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / US Budget: Dollars 1m pay earners comb the fine print -
Salary curb
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration's plan to curb excessive executive pay by ending
the tax deductibility of salaries of more than Dollars 1m (Pounds 660,720)
will still leave companies considerable leeway.
The economic package published in February said salaries above Dollars 1m
could still be deducted if the pay were linked to the company's performance.
More detailed proposals published by the US Treasury this week show that
performance-linked pay would include not only commissions or other earnings
based directly on an executive's percentage of sales, but also any
compensation package based on performance standards approved by the
company's shareholders.
These standards would have to be set up by independent directors of the
company.
The ban on deductibility would affect only the chief executive and the four
other highest paid executives in a company - a limit which is expected to
help Wall Street firms that may have many more employees earning more than
Dollars 1m - and compensation plans already in place before the measure was
outlined on February 17 would also be exempted.
Compensation consultants appeared to be divided over how onerous the
proposal would be for companies, with much remaining to be determined by the
precise regulations that are eventually published to implement the measure.
Much may depend, for example, on how much detail the Treasury will require
companies to give shareholders before they vote on any compensation package.
President Clinton has said the measure is to encourage companies to examine
pay policies with the goal of helping 'shift business spending from excess
pay to investment'.
</TEXT>
