<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / Poland faces shift to left
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Poland's coalition government, led by Ms Hanna Suchocka, faces a reshuffle
and possible shift to the left, following the resignation of Mr Gabriel
Janowski, agriculture minister, Christopher Bobinski reports from Warsaw.
Mr Janowski quit after the government brushed aside his ministry's
recommendations on minimum grain prices. He attacked cabinet colleagues for
failing to support his efforts to develop agriculture.
About 40 per cent of Poles live or work in the countryside and the rural
vote is important.
Leaders of Mr Janowski's party will meet next week to decide whether to
withdraw from the coalition. If they pull out, Ms Suchocka may turn to the
left-leaning PSL farmers' party.
Reuter adds: Poland's secret service have foiled a plot to kill President
Lech Walesa, a spokeswoman for the service said yesterday.
