<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRONG two-way business in index options boosted total turnover as London's
derivatives market announced the introduction of eight new equity options
contracts, writes Joel Kibazo.
Having been in the doldrums over the previous two sessions, business in the
traded options showed a marked improvement and turnover by the close had
reached 39,817 contracts. Some 10,762 lots were dealt in the FT-SE 100
option, while the Euro FT-SE option was also heavily traded at 9,218
contracts.
In the stock options, Asda Group was the most active with a total of 5,994
contracts and was followed by Hanson at 2,507. BT and Hillsdown were also
heavily traded.
The Liffe yesterday announced the introduction of eight new equity options
contracts, taking the number traded to 70.
The new contracts are Argyll Group, National Westminster Bank, Redland,
Royal Insurance, Tarmac, Tomkins, Williams Holdings and Zeneca. All with the
exception of Zeneca will be traded from May 12. Options in Eurotunnel, GKN,
Vaal Reefs and Scottish &amp; Newcastle are being phased out.
In futures, the June contract on the FT-SE 100 opened at 2,843 and drifted
lower for the rest of the day to end at 2,828, down 17 from its previous
close and at a 5-point premium to the underlying cash market. Volume was
9,584 lots.
</TEXT>
