<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Late program buying helps Dow
to improve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices ended firmer yesterday after gains in certain sectors -
notably transportation and brokerage stocks - and some late program buying
helped the markets recover from losses incurred earlier in the week among
consumer issues, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 19.45 up at 3,397.02. The Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 index gained 1.57 at 442.73 and the Nasdaq composite firmed
4.74 to 668.88. Trading volume on the New York SE totalled 298m shares.
The markets still lacked an overall clear direction, a reflection of
nervousness following the recent sell-off in leading consumer stocks such as
Wal-Mart and Home Depot, and of the cautious approach investors were
adopting ahead of the all-important inflation news due out today and
tomorrow, when the March producer and consumer indices will be published.
Recent gains in commodity prices, coupled with continued strength in certain
areas of the economy, have revived fears that inflationary pressures may be
building up. Those fears have trimmed prices in bond and stock markets and,
if the March prices data comes in stronger than expected, analysts warn that
equity prices could tumble.
Some individual sectors performed strongly. Airlines were generally higher
amid hopes that the recent restructuring in the industry would eventually
lead to a return to profitability for the country's biggest carriers. Among
the leading stocks, UAL (which announced further cuts in aircraft order
costs yesterday) jumped Dollars 9 7/8 to Dollars 137, Delta added Dollars 3
3/4 at Dollars 57 1/4 , USAir advanced Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 24 1/4 and
AMR, parent of American Airlines, climbed Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 69.
Brokerage issues were also in demand, following record quarterly results
from Bear Stearns for the January-to-March reporting period. Bear Stearns
ended Dollars 1 1/8 ahead at Dollars 19, Merrill Lynch up Dollars 1 3/8 at
Dollars 69 1/4 and PaineWebber Dollars 1 higher at Dollars 24 7/8 .
Home Depot bounced back from losses incurred earlier in the week, rallying
Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 58 in volume of 3.6m shares. US Surgical fell
Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 46 1/2 after a Dean Witter analyst changed his
recommendation on the stock to 'sell' from 'neutral' and cut his forecast
for 1993 sales and profits because he fears the company has over-estimated
future sales of its tools for laparoscopic surgeons.
Advanced Micro Devices rose Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 25 1/8 in volume of
2.3m shares after Warburg, the securities house, raised its investment
rating on the stock from 'add' to 'buy', citing the company's better than
expected first-quarter results.
Canada
AFTER trading in negative territory for most of the day, Toronto saw a
modest last-hour rally which left shares closing mixed with just a slightly
easier bias. Trading was again heavy.
The TSE 300 index was finally up 2.6 at 3,601.4 but declines led advances by
358 to 324 after volume of 59.0m shares valued at CDollars 513.8m.
</TEXT>
