FT  08 APR 93 / International Company News: Greek private bank to set up
unit in Romania
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CREDIT Bank, Greece's largest private bank, is setting up a bank in Romania
in which the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) will
take an equity stake.
The new bank, to be called Bank of Bucharest, will have start-up capital of
Dollars 10m. It will be the first foreign-owned bank to open in the country
since the overthrow of the Communist government in 1989.
The EBRD is to contribute Dollars 2.5m in equity, with the remainder being
covered by a holding company controlled by Credit Bank, in which several
Greek businessmen will have minority holdings. The new bank will be managed
by Alpha Finance, the merchant banking arm of Credit Bank. It is expected to
start operating by the end of 1993.
Mr Panagis Vourloumis, managing director of Alpha Finance, said the bank
would look for opportunities offered by Romania's privatisation programme as
well as financing trade carried out by a growing number of Greek-Romanian
joint ventures.
