<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Barclays closes book on unhappy chapter: How the bank hopes
to avoid the mistakes of the past
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE short, unhappy life of the Barclays Bank division that let property
lending get out of hand in the late 1980s is at least ending with a bang
rather than a whimper. The bank will tell its managers today that the
Central Advances Department is to disappear, along with the executive in
charge.
Mr Mark Deverell, whose misfortune was to be made director of risk
management of Barclays in 1989 amid what turned out to be a catastrophic
lending boom, is leaving the bank. His job has been abolished as Barclays
reforms the way it assesses loan risks, and balances its portfolio.
Mr Alan Brown, who takes the equivalent post in the new structure, does not
mince words about the failure of the CAD, founded in the early 1980s. He
says the lending following Barclays' Pounds 921m rights issue in 1988 was
too much for managers who had to approve loans and monitor the portfolio.
'We undoubtedly feel that we were too aggressive in that period. That means
you take on business at a speed which makes your executives so busy that
they cannot be as thorough as they could be before.'
He says the balance of loans was distorted towards property, construction
and hotels because the 500 managers and staff under Mr Deverell were
swamped: 'We had the classic business dilemma of choosing between things
that are important and things that are urgent. The balance was wrong.'
The effect can be seen by comparing Barclays' portfolio and provisions with
those of National Westminster, the second largest UK bank by assets. The
banks have lent in roughly the same proportions to most sectors, but
Barclays has more exposure to property and construction.
Barclays was always strong in property and construction. But the two sectors
proved far more risky than in the past. Together, they accounted for only
11.9 per cent of its loan book last year. But 38 per cent of its Pounds
1.96bn provision against UK lending in the UK related to them.
A second problem was over the approval and monitoring of individual loans.
Each loan of more than Pounds 5m was approved by at least one executive in
CAD, and monitored by the bank's risk management committee. This comprised
senior directors and executives which reviewed bad debts and exposures.
Mr Brown says that this committee - in spite of the emphasis placed on it in
Barclays' annual report - met infrequently. 'They did not meet on individual
loans unless there was a special reason. They passed the proposition around.
The first person signed, and then the second, and so on.'
So although Barclays in theory had a system of checks and balances to
monitor loans, in practice the CAD was too busy to balance the portfolio
well, and the risk committee hardly discussed individual loans. 'There was a
danger that because the first person said yes, so did the others,' he says.
Under Barclays' new structure - in place this month - there will be three
changes.
The first is that Mr Brown will head the new 'group credit policy unit'
which will monitor exposures and balancing the portfolio. Mr Brown says this
means there will be a smaller proportion of property lending, as well as
shifts in country exposure, and the re-pricing of loans in some other
lending areas.
'We have still got a big business here. We are not talking about dumping
whole categories of customers, but of lightening the load in certain areas,'
he says. He expects that over two years, the bank will be able to rebalance
its portfolio to match a new computer model of credit risk it is developing.
The model is expected to be applied to all but the smallest loans within a
year. It rates risk according to factors such as industry sector, company
size and history, and financial information. Barclays has drawn it up using
data on large loans dating back six years in the UK.
Mr Brown emphasises that he sees his task as rebalancing the portfolio
rather than growing Barclays' balance sheet. 'It is patently obvious from
our results that we could have lent the same amount of money, and if we had
lost less of it, we would have a better net result,' he says.
The second change is that the loan approval responsibility of the CAD will
be broken up. Instead, there will be separate risk management departments
within the banking and investment banking divisions. This is intended to
give a greater sense of responsibility for loans to those who make them.
All loans which would have had to be approved within the CAD previously will
be allocated to a single 'responsible executive' within the line divisions.
This executive - drawn from about 150 around the world - will have to follow
each loan through to the end.
'There should be less chance of a line person saying 'It is my job to
deliver as many propositions to you as possible, and the ones that go right
will get me a bonus, and the ones that go wrong are down to you',' says Mr
Brown. The third change is that the risk management committee is being
scrapped and a 'group credit committee' put in its place. This will be
chaired by Mr Humphrey Norrington, a vice-chairman of Barclays, and will
meet daily to discuss individual exposures of above Pounds 150m.
'They are similar directors from the ones who signed the very largest
credits before, but in order to get a more active discussion they will meet
if necessary every day for a short period,' says Mr Brown. He says the bank
wants to promote a debate about risks that was largely absent before.
Will this new scrutiny leave a bank that just looks like all the rest? Mr
Brown says it wants to remain distinctive, but its traditions will be under
scrutiny. 'Where we are different, we will want to have asked ourselves why
in a diligent, professional manner.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
