<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Danger of Stalin's secret N-plants: Leyla Boulton recently
visited the site of Tuesday's nuclear leak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IRON GATES, rows of barbed wire, searchlights and armed guards separate
Tomsk-7, Stalin's secret nuclear city in western Siberia, from the outside
world.
This is the site of a radioactive explosion on Tuesday night which has
heightened fears about the once-pampered defence plants of the former Soviet
Union which are still involved in the production of nuclear weapons.
The International Atomic Energy Agency in Vienna yesterday put the Tomsk
accident at Level Three on the International Nuclear Events Scale. That
means 'a serious incident with on-site contamination but no effects
off-site'. Chernobyl was a Level Seven disaster.
However, a radioactive cloud was last night reported to be moving across
Siberia away from Tomsk-7 and the nearby city of Tomsk. Russian television
said the cloud was moving northeast at a height of 1.2 miles and a speed of
22 mph. The environmental group Greenpeace said several villages were at
risk from wind-borne fallout. Russian officials in Tomsk tested snow for
radiation.
International environmental groups have blamed lax safety standards at the
plant and said the international community should press Russia to stop
plutonium production immediately. Anti-nuclear activists urged US president
Bill Clinton to make his Dollars 1.6bn (Pounds 1.05bn) aid package, offered
at last weekend's Vancouver summit, contingent upon Russia halting
production of civilian and military plutonium.
However, Mr John Gittus, director-general of the British Nuclear Industry
Forum, which monitors nuclear incidents around the world, said the incident
was nowhere near as bad as the 1986 Chernobyl disaster. 'There can be no
comparison between this incident and what happened at Chernobyl seven years
ago,' he said.
On a recent visit there the Financial Times was allowed to see only the prim
administrative and residential centre, with solid, pastel-colour Stalin-era
houses, amid beautiful Siberian forest.
But Professor Alexei Yablokov, President Boris Yeltsin's adviser on ecology
and health, said his wife, a journalist, had seen 'rusting locks and leaking
roofs' at nuclear-related facilities there.
The incident at the Tomsk-7 chemical plant was the first at the heart of
Russia's secretive defence industry to be openly and promptly acknowledged.
Tomsk-7, established by Stalin to develop a nuclear bomb, is today a town of
110,000 people, producing plutonium and enriched uranium for nuclear
weapons.
Mr Gennady Khandorin, director of the chemical plant, said the reasons for a
build-up of pressure which destroyed a container of radioactive material
were still unknown. He said his staff were fine and only a stretch of road
outside the plant had suffered from 'very small, local contamination'.
The incident was nonetheless the worst in the former Soviet Union since
Chernobyl.
Special permission is required for a visit to Tomsk-7's two reactors, which
produce nuclear fuel from which uranium and plutonium are derived, plus the
chemical works where components for nuclear weapons are developed.,
Moscow is proposing to make Tomsk-7 the site of a national repository for
plutonium from nuclear weapons dismantled under arms reduction treaties, and
the US Congress has pledged Dollars 400m to fund such a facility. The
incident is likely to put this plan into question.
Despite Tomsk-7's desire to open up to the outside world - not least because
of a reduction in special state support which used to make its isolation
profitable - it is the victim of difficulties in transforming Russia's
military-industrial machine.
Mr Nicolai Yegorov, deputy atomic energy minister, said last month that
Tomsk-7 had to continue to produce fresh plutonium until it had a centre in
which to recycle the ageing plutonium which needs to be replaced
periodically in nuclear weapons not covered by arms treaties.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9511 Air, Water, and Solid Waste Management.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>RES  Pollution.
    RES  Facilities.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
