<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / John Major's Year: Red tape makes it harder to scratch a
living - Small-businessman John Millington says the other JM should pay more
attention to domestic problems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF IT has been a tough year for Mr John Major, it has hardly been one long
party for Mr John Millington.
He has been working up to 14 hours a day, seven days a week, to keep his
one-man business alive, and seems, possibly like the prime minister, a
little surprised to have survived. Mr Millington, an engraver by profession
and Liverpudlian by birth, owns Adams Engraving in Woking. He bought it 18
months ago as the economy slid deeper into recession. He had applied for the
job of manager but put his house on the line to buy the business: 'Everyone
thought I was crazy,' he recalls.
The company, which specialises in engraving everything from golf club
trophies to aero-engine components, had a small base of regular customers
and turnover of Pounds 35,000 a year. Now, in spite of weak demand, a long
period of high interest rates and rising raw material prices, Mr Millington
has pushed turnover to about Pounds 68,000. It should reach Pounds 80,000
this year and the plan is start recruiting by Christmas.
But Mr Major has not made life any easier for the small enterprises they
claim to champion, says Mr Millington. Britain's departure from the exchange
rate mechanism meant a sharp rise in the cost of German-made brass and he
has been unable to pass on the increase to customers.
He also paints a familiar picture of bureaucratic interference and
commercial ignorance among officials.
'They constantly claim they are banishing red tape but I have yet to see any
evidence. People are urged to take up their redundancy pay and have a go for
themselves, but the environment for small businesses is still hostile. The
VAT people can be vicious and now we are awaiting our first visit from the
Inland Revenue. Now I have to implement a quality standard which is going to
cost me thousands and take two years. Where is the understanding?' He says
Mr Major's greatest strength is his negotiating ability, as demonstrated in
Europe, but he wants him to pay more attention to the nation's domestic
problems.
'We need stronger leadership. People need encouragement and the confidence
to go out and set up the small engineering shops which will help restore the
manufacturing skills we have been losing. The priority must be for big
capital projects which will work through to the benefit of everyone down the
chain.'
This holiday weekend, Mr Millington and his wife, Barbara, who keeps the
books, will take a well-earned break from the daily struggle. He regularly
asks himself if it is worth the effort: 'I suppose being your own boss still
means the answer is yes.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
