<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Employers face EC curbs on ability to cut pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYERS' ability to reduce pay and conditions at short notice will be
seriously impaired by a little-noticed clause the European Commission has
forced the government to insert into the Trade Union Reform and Employment
Rights Bill, employers' organisations said yesterday.
At present employers can generally give a few days' notice of terminating an
existing employment contract, after which employees are technically
dismissed and then offered re-employment on less favourable terms.
During the recession many employers have been making, or trying to make,
such changes, most notably Rolls-Royce in 1991. Sometimes employees accept
the new terms but they are often resisted and, if employers are judged to
have introduced the changes unfairly, employees can win damages at an
industrial tribunal.
But a clause in the Employment Rights Bill, designed to bring British law
fully into line with the EC's Collective Redundancies directive and due to
become law this summer, means that employers are likely to have to give 90
days' notice in the case of such technical dismissals.
Previously the directive insisted on 90 days' notice only for ordinary
redundancies where 100 or more employees were losing their jobs. The
Employment Rights Bill introduces a more broad definition of redundancy to
include 'dismissal for a reason not related to the individual concerned'.
The Institute of Directors said it was 'concerned' about the effects of the
change. 'We made representations to the government about this but they said
there was no problem,' it said.
A TUC official welcomed the change, saying it brought British law into line
with the original directive. Other changes include the obligation on
employers to 'seek to reach agreement with trade union representatives' on
redundancies.
The commission had been threatening legal action against Britain if it did
not incorporate these points. Legal action may continue over the fact that
in Britain consultation over redundancies is required only where unions are
recognised.
</TEXT>
