<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Legal aid restrictions to go ahead: Law Society wins leave
to challenge Mackay's move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD MACKAY, the lord chancellor, is to go ahead with cuts in legal aid
eligibility from next week in spite of a High Court ruling yesterday
allowing the Law Society to challenge the validity of his proposals.
The solicitors' governing body was granted leave to seek a judicial review
of the lord chancellor's plans after Lord Mackay decided not to oppose its
application. Mr Justice Macpherson said the case should be heard as soon as
possible in view of the 'enormous public interest'. The hearing is expected
to take place at the end of May.
Mr Michael Beloff QC, for the society, told the judge both sides had reached
'a combined view' that the issues raised by the case should be argued at a
full High Court hearing.
He said that 'in the circumstances' the society would not be applying for a
court order suspending the changes - due to come into force on day - until
after the legal challenge had been concluded.
The society maintains that the changes, which will reduce the qualifying
disposable income limit for free legal aid to income-support levels and
increase the contributions paid by others towards their cases, could affect
up to 14m people in England and Wales.
Lord Mackay has dismissed those figures as 'absurd'. He maintains that in
practical terms about 120,000 of the 3m people who receive financial
assistance from the scheme each year would be affected.
After yesterday's hearing the Lord Chancellor's Department said the
challenge would be 'strongly opposed'.
It added: 'In the meantime the lord chancellor does not propose to delay the
April 12 implementation of the regulations, which were debated and approved
in the House of Commons on March 31.'
It was 'administratively too difficult' to withdraw the regulations at this
stage, it said. If they were eventually ruled unlawful only a few people
would have been affected in the weeks they were in force.
Mr Mark Sheldon, the society's president, last night wrote to Lord Mackay
urging him to think again and suspend the regulations.
'If the regulations come into force on April 12, many people who have an
urgent need for legal advice - perhaps to avoid eviction or to obtain an
injunction in a domestic violence case - will be irreparably prejudiced,
whatever the court's final decision,' he said.
This is the second time in a month that the society has won permission to
challenge the legal aid proposals.
In March the same judge gave the society leave to seek a judicial review of
the lord chancellor's plans to introduce standard fees for criminal legal
aid work in magistrates' courts. That challenge will be heard on April 29.
In both cases the society alleges that Lord Mackay has acted outside his
powers under the 1988 Legal Aid Act.
The society claims his proposals on standard fees for criminal work are
contrary to the principle set out in the act that a solicitor is entitled to
'fair remuneration' for a case.
In the latest case the society says the regulations were made without proper
consultation as required by the act.
</TEXT>
