FT  08 APR 93 / Salvation Army to break silence on missing Pounds 6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Salvation Army is preparing to break its silence on the circumstances
surrounding an alleged Pounds 6m fraud by publishing an interim report on
the affair.
The charity has refused to comment on the alleged fraud since it surfaced on
February 15 when a writ was issued in the High Court. The writ alleged that
Tilen Securities Inc and Birmingham businessman Mr Stuart Ford and Mr Gamil
Naguib conspired to defraud the charity of the money.
The charity has maintained that it had to balance the public's right to know
the facts with the need to recover the missing money. It was advised by its
lawyers that to make any statements would jeopardise that recovery.
Senior charity officials now appear to be responding to internal pressure to
clarify what, if any, are the charity's own responsibilities in the matter
although only a small proportion of the missing money has been recovered.
In two weeks the charity's High Council of senior representatives from the
its various 'territories' meet to elect the new head or 'general' of the
organisation. The present general, Ms Eva Burroughs, has reached the end of
her five-year term.
It is felt that the incoming general should take up the post without the
affair remaining unresolved.
The Salvation Army last night confirmed that it planned to make an interim
statement shortly following meetings with its lawyers and Coopers &amp; Lybrand,
the accountancy firm which has been investigating the alleged fraud for the
charity.
The statement may shed some light on the future of Colonel Grenville Burn,
who was in charge of the charity's fundraising and was involved in contacts
between the charity and Mr Naguib and Mr Ford. Col Burn has been officially
on sick leave since writs were issued and refused to comment last night.
