<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Crisis talks held to avert rail strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL is holding separate talks today with the two main rail unions
in an attempt to prevent the second 24-hour strike on the network which is
due to take place on Friday next week.
Mr Paul Watkinson, British Rail's personnel director, said last night the
corporation could not afford any more damaging disruption on the railway
network. Last Friday's stoppage cost British Rail Pounds 10m in lost fare
income.
The meetings scheduled for today follow an announcement yesterday by Aslef,
the train drivers' union, that it intends to join the 24-hour stoppage
planned by the RMT, the main rail union, for April 16 in protest at the
threat of compulsory redundancies.
British Rail said in its invitation to the rail unions for talks that it
wanted to 'clarify' the problems. But the RMT said last night that it was
going into the discussions with the intention of 'negotiating positively and
constructively'.
Some 67 per cent of Aslef members voted in a postal ballot by 55 per cent to
45 per cent to support a one-day stoppage followed by a rolling programme of
industrial action.
At the moment, the prospect of an early settlement of the disputes with both
Aslef and the RMT looks remote. Mr Derrick Fullick, Aslef's general
secretary, said yesterday that British Rail must honour existing national
agreements that cover job security, and added that he was not convinced by
British Rail's present assurances.
The RMT wants British Rail to accept there should be no future compulsory
redundancies and to agree to a ban on contract work. So far British Rail has
said it could not agree to these demands.
If today's talks fail to achieve a breakthrough British Rail may be forced
to adopt tougher tactics than it has done so far.
Some senior managers are in favour of confronting the rail unions, but so
far British Rail has adopted a conciliatory approach.
</TEXT>
