<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / 'Bored' junior auditors take short cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUNIOR AUDITORS take short cuts in their work while older tax accountants
tend to sympathise more with the Inland Revenue than their clients,
according to two academic papers circulated yesterday at the British
Accounting Association annual conference in Glasgow.
Only 22 per cent of a sample of 112 newly qualified accountants had not
indulged in 'irregular audit practices', Ms Caroline Willett and Mr Michael
Page of the University of Portsmouth said.
As a result of time pressure, more than half of the respondents said they
had been tempted to reject awkward-looking items from an audit sample, and a
quarter were tempted to accept audit evidence about which they were
doubtful. A total of 30 per cent had been tempted to hasten audit testing
because they believed the work was boring and 41 per cent because they
thought it was unimportant.
The findings, if they are representative, may cause embarrassment to
accountancy firms but some academics at the conference criticised the
research methods used. The researchers were accused of asking leading
questions.
In a separate study, researchers from the University of Bradford said that
taxpayers who were looking for a tax adviser sympathetic to their burdens
should seek out someone young, professionally qualified and practising in a
firm with no fewer than three partners.
The study found that decisions taken by advisers depended on factors such as
age and formal training, as well as technical knowledge of the tax system
and interpretation of tax law.
Based on a survey of 113 practitioners, the researchers concluded that most
had a high standard of morality over the issue of taxpayers withholding
information.
A third said they would inform only the client if information had been
deliberately withheld. Two thirds said they would also inform the Inland
Revenue. But the proportion who would contact the Revenue rose from 31 per
cent for those aged up to 35, to 83 per cent for those older than 50.
</TEXT>
