<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Staff shares 'help attitude'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A SIGNIFICANT increase in the number of employee share schemes over the past
decade has helped improve workers' attitudes towards work, although they
might not be working any harder, a report in today's Employment Gazette, the
journal of the Department of Employment, says.
Drawing on a survey jointly commissioned by the department, the Inland
Revenue and the Treasury, the report says schemes are more common in the
finance, banking, insurance and business services sectors.
'An important part of the explanation for this is that awareness of tax
advantages and financial matters in general tends to be higher in these
sectors,' says the report.
Schemes, particularly Save As You Earn schemes, were also more prevalent in
large quoted companies, the report adds.
Employee involvement was the most important effect sought by companies that
introduced share schemes.
