<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Hope raised for fraud trials
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRAUD TRIALS should be shorter and juries better informed after the Court of
Appeal judgment that the Serious Fraud Office can use all information given
to company liquidators under compulsion as evidence in court, an appeal
court judge said yesterday.
Three appeal judges gave their reasons behind the judgment, delivered last
month, that the SFO could have full access to transcripts of interviews
carried out by administrators using their powers under the Insolvency Act to
compel interviewees to answer questions. The SFO can use this information
freely as evidence in court, they ruled.
The issue had been taken to appeal by Mr Kevin Maxwell, Mr Larry
Trachtenberg and Mr Muhammed Naviede, head of the Arrows group, who all face
fraud charges brought by the SFO. All three have also been interviewed by
administrators using Insolvency Act powers.
The judges said the Insolvency Act 1986 did not limit provisions in the
Criminal Justice Act 1987, which established the SFO. They also rejected
arguments by Robson Rhodes, the liquidators of Bishopsgate Investment
Management, and from administrators of other Maxwell companies, that the
SFO's powers should be restricted to enable liquidation operations to be
carried out speedily and effectively.
Lord Justice Steyn said the ruling 'will enable the contextual scene, such
as the hierarchy of companies, the role of individuals, the flow of funds,
and like matters, to be placed before the jury far more effectively than has
hitherto been regarded as possible'.
He added that it should 'improve the chances of the SFO system functioning
more efficiently'.
</TEXT>
