<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / World Trade News: Kantor welcomes French truce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SIGNALS that the new French government wanted 'trade peace' were welcomed
yesterday by Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, writes Nancy Dunne
in Washington. He called for relations between the 'two new governments' to
be placed on a 'more positive footing'.
Mr Kantor last week came under fire when, on his first visit as trade
representative to the European Community, he refused to offer the usual US
homilies about free trade. His insistence on a pragmatic, market-opening
policy raised fears that the US would close its own market if its demands
were not met.
Apparently anxious to show his desire for trade peace, Mr Kantor responded
to statements on Tuesday by Mr Edouard Balladur, the new French prime
minister, who said that although he would press for 'improvements' to the
global farm trade agreement, he wanted 'trade peace with Washington'. The
French premier added he did not want to cause a crisis within the EC or the
Uruguay Round negotiations over farm trade.
